<subSubSection lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="52" pageId="4" pageNumber="51" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="51">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="51">
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Orthaltica" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Orthaltica terminalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="terminalia">Orthaltica terminalia</taxonomicName>
can be easily distinguished from all known Indian 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Orthaltica" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Orthaltica" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Orthaltica</taxonomicName>
species using the key below. 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Orthaltica" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Orthaltica syzygium" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="syzygium">Orthaltica syzygium</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from the most similar species using the following characters: body shiny black (Fig. 16); vertex with four long and six short setae (Fig. 18); elytra sparsely pubescent (Figs 16 &amp; 17); apex of aedeagus narrowing abruptly (Fig. 19); spermatheca with thin elongate pump (Fig. 21). 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Orthaltica" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Orthaltica minuta subsp. indica" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="minuta" subSpecies="indica">Orthaltica minuta indica</taxonomicName>
(Medevedev) is not included in the key as there is no character to separate it from 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Orthaltica" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Orthaltica dakshina" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dakshina">Orthaltica dakshina</taxonomicName>
(Basu &amp; Sengupta). Both species are from the same locality (Doddabetta in Tamil Nadu) and further research may prove them to be synonymous.
</paragraph>
